title: Hillary Clinton Was Confident but Not Entitled in the Debate
text:
Confident but Not Entitled In the debate, Hillary Clinton proved she deserves to be the Democratic front-runner. By Susan Milligan Oct. 16, 2015 | 6:00 a.m. EDT
+ More Hillary Clinton had the biggest challenge in the Democratic debate, and she met it easily: proving that she deserves her early status as the front-runner.
Confident but not entitled, a well-prepared Clinton sparred amiably with her four opponents, even getting an assist from Vermont Sen. Bernie Sanders, who declared himself "sick and tired of hearing about your damn emails." Lincoln Chafee, in characteristic honesty, acknowledged that he didn't really know what he was voting for when he voted to undo a major piece of banking legislation. Jim Webb failed to stand out with his repeated references to his Vietnam War record, while Martin O'Malley served the party – if not himself – by reminding viewers what the Democratic field offered: a seat at the grown-ups table, without the personal insults that have characterized the GOP debates.
